    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mr. Taruskin writes "Unless subversively performed . . . the repertory that  Beethoven begot has to a distressing extent turned into . . . a stagnant pond."  His main point in this faddish article seems to be that Beethoven has not written anything new since his death.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mr. Taruskin writes "Unless subversively performed . . . the repertory that  Beethoven begot has to a distressing extent turned into . . . a stagnant pond."  His main point in this faddish article seems to be that Beethoven has not written anything new since his death.</p>
        <p>A week later, in "No Praise for Pop? It's a Bum Rap" [Sept. 17], Bernard Holland takes a similar view. He decries the loss of a "lingua franca" for classical music. Present-day composers may be struggling to find a new language; however, the rich language of the past is still alive, and it can be learned with some effort. These critics should be aware than many people do not listen to pop music for the same reason they do not read romance novels.</p>
        <p>T. F. MORSE Providence, R.I.</p>
        <p>BEETHOVEN</p>
      </block>
